text: Beach seine fishing for salmon in River Feale near by town Ballybunion, year 1975. The River Feale (An Fhéil or Abhainn na Féile in Irish) rises near Rockchapel in the Mullaghareirk Mountains of County Cork in the southwest of Ireland and flows northwestwards for 75 kilometres Fishing in Ireland.info through Abbeyfeale in County Limerick and Listowel in County Kerry before finally emptying into the Mouth of the Shannon by Ballyduff. Then it flows out through the Shannon's estuary and joins with the Atlantic Ocean with a flow rate of 34.6 m2/s. Case Study Report - Shannon River Basin The river, along with its tributaries, combine to add to over 160 km (100 miles) of waterways. The river contains a large salmon and sea trout population. ==Name== According to Geoffrey Keating's Foras Feasa ar Éirinn (compiled in the 1630s), the river takes its name from a legendary woman:http://www.ucc.ie/celt/online/T100054/text032.htmlhttp://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/G100054/index.html ==See also== * Rivers of Ireland * Shannon River Basin ==References== Category:Rivers of County Kerry Category:Rivers of County Cork
